dfischer.utils

Class HttpResponseContentPerformanceDataReceiveSegmentInfo

  • java.lang.Object
    • dfischer.utils.HttpResponseContentPerformanceDataReceiveSegmentInfo

  • public class HttpResponseContentPerformanceDataReceiveSegmentInfo
extends java.lang.Object
    Contains performance data about the receiving of one single data segment of the HTTP response content.

    • Constructor Summary

      Create a new instance.

    • Method Summary

      Methods 
      Modifier and Type Method and Description
      long getAbsoluteNanoTime()
      Get the OS time in nanoseconds when the read-operation of the data segment was started (see also java.lang.System.nanoTime()).
      long getDeltaNanoTime()
      Get the delta time in nanoseconds of the read-operation, used to wait for new data and to read the received data segment.
      int getSegmentSize()
      Get the size of the received data segment in bytes.
      boolean isChunkIdentifierData()
      Return if the data segment contains chunk identifier data (see RFC 2616 for further details; section 3.6.1 in particular).

      • HttpResponseContentPerformanceDataReceiveSegmentInfo

        public HttpResponseContentPerformanceDataReceiveSegmentInfo(long absoluteNanoTime,
                                                    long deltaNanoTime,
                                                    int segentSize,
                                                    boolean isChunkIdentifierData)
        Create a new instance.
        Parameters:
        absoluteNanoTime - the OS time in nanoseconds when the read-operation of the data segment was started (see also java.lang.System.nanoTime())
        deltaNanoTime - delta nano time of the read-operation, used to wait for new data and to read the received data segment
        segentSize - the size of the received data segment in bytes
        isChunkIdentifierData - specifies if the data segment contains "chunk identifier data" (true), or if the data segment contains "user data" (false) such as HTML, image or video data. See RFC 2616 for further details; section 3.6.1 in particular.
